published:"2019-09-23T09:29:00-07:00",updated:"2020-06-05T19:11:38-07:00",url:"http://www.fecklessthug.com/2019/09/amazing-recent-science-discoveries_23.html",selfLink:"https://www.googleapis.com/blogger/v3/blogs/9198389381789324893/posts/2654526081806887748",title:"Amazing Recent Science Discoveries!",content:"DNA is held together by hydrophobic forces -- not hydrogen-bonds!<br />\n<br />\nthe discovery was made at chalmers university of technology, sweden.\n<br />\n<br />\namazing water...\n<br />\n<br />\nthe building-blocks of dna are sugar molecules and phosphate groups --\n<br />\nnitrogen bases are between the sugar molecules and phosphate groups.\n<br />\n<br />\npreviously, hydrogen-bonds were assumed to\n<br />\nhave held together the sugar and phosphates.\n<br />\n<br />\nnow, it seems, the nitrogen-bases of the dna molecules have\n<br />\na hydrophobic interior -- a mostly water environment -- where\n<br />\nthe bases group together to push away and help avoid the water.\n<br />\n<br />\nthese hydrophobic-forces seem to hold the dna-helixes together!\n<br />\n<br />\nthe hydrogen-bonds have relegated their role to<br />\nsimply sorting base-pairs into correct sequences --\n<br />\nrather than holding the dna-helixes togther.\n<br />\n<br />\na catalytic protein creates the water-based environment.<br />\n<br />\ncatalytic-proteins are critical to dna repairs --\n<br />\nwhich means the discovery may be a<br />\nnew key to fighting our bio-enemies.\n<br />\n<br />\nfor example, the RecA protein is used by bacteria to repair their dna --\n<br />\nunderstanding how repairs function could provide new methods of attack.\n<br />\n<br />\nas mostly an aside: after they were long famous, watson and crick\n<br />\nwere said to have noted that, if they were young biologists today,\n<br />\nthey would concentrate their studies on proteins.\n<br />\n<br />\npublication: proceedings of the national academy of sciences.\n<br />\n<br />\n(b) a new bee species was discovered in fiji: homalictus terminalis \n<br />\nachrostus --\n<br />\nthe name was chosen to represent the likely near-term extinction, based on\n<br />\nmodern biological stressors of multiple environmental risk factors.\n<br />\n<br />\nthe bee appears to be black with bright reds\n<br />\nand oranges and colorful translucent wings.\n<br />\n<br />\nh. achrostus has only ever found on a single mountain top in fuji.\n<br />\n<br />\npublication: zootaxa.\n<br />\n<br />\n(c) a new mineral was discovered in south africa: goldschmidtite --\n<br />\nthe name was chosen to honor the amazing geochemist, mineralogist,\n<br />\ncrystal-chemist, and geochemistist, victor moritz goldschmidt.\n<br />\n<br />\nthe never-before-seen mineral was a single, tiny, grain or rock\n<br />\nwedged within a diamond that was created by the earth's natural\n<br />\npressure, hundreds of miles underground.\n<br />\n<br />\ngoldschmidtite seems to be rich in niobium, potassium,\n<br />\nand the rare-earth elements lanthanum and cerium.\n<br />\n<br />\nthe new mineral was found near the koffiefontein pipe --\n<br />\na volcanic shaft, into the earth, of volcanic origin.\n<br />\n<br />\npublication: journal american mineralogist.",
