blog:{id:"9198389381789324893"},published:"2007-10-29T23:50:00-07:00",updated:"2019-04-18T02:33:29-07:00",url:"http://www.fecklessthug.com/2007/10/b-f-skinner-et-al.html",selfLink:"https://www.googleapis.com/blogger/v3/blogs/9198389381789324893/posts/4990870610914958567",title:"psychology, b. f. skinner, et. al.",content:'science is neither for or against religion;<br />\none may attempt to apply science to interactions<br />\nwithin religious groups -- but that is not,<br />\nand should not be, at all the same act, as being<br />\nfair or balanced with respect to such groups.<br />\n<br />\nif scientists were interested in the fair<br />\nand balanced treatment of religion they should<br />\nmost probably seek another profession.<br />\n<br />\nthere may be obvious connections between<br />\ncognitive dissonance theory and how people<br />\nare susceptible to the social pressures of<br />\njoining groups; but any fair or balanced<br />\nnotion of a particular group doesn\'t apply --<br />\nexcept in the context of a particular experiment.<br />\n<br />\nthe fair and balanced notion of science<br />\nis simply that science is uncertain.<br />\n<br />\nwhat we should strive for is not the mixing of<br />\nreligion into science -- but the goal of allowing<br />\nthe humility of the spirit that is religion<br />\nand the humility of the intellect that is science<br />\nto coexist, stand apart, mutually unafraid.<br />\n<a href="https://www.google.com/search?tbm=shop&amp;q=%22behavior+psychology+driven%22"><br />\n<img src="https://images.cafepress.com/product/177902673_150x150_Front.jpg" /></a>',
